From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Christopher Ayers <brianboitano87@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 2026 08:45:52 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] nvmoe: page routed experts from an nvmoe pack (CPU
 correctness stage)

Loading a pack's resident.gguf (detected via the nvmoe.pack.version KV)
now works end to end: the routed-expert weights are never loaded into
memory. Instead, src/llama-nvmoe.{h,cpp} owns pool tensors
[ne0, ne1, n_slots] per matrix kind, shared across layers with the same
geometry, backed by an LRU cache keyed (layer, expert). build_moe_ffn()
inserts a custom op on the selected-experts ids that synchronously
fetches missing experts from experts.pack (O_DIRECT pread) and remaps
the ids to pool slots, so ggml_mul_mat_id runs unchanged. Everything
indexed by real expert id (routing probs, per-expert biases) keeps the
original ids.

Cache size defaults to all experts resident; NVMOE_CACHE_MB caps it
(floored at n_expert slots per group so any single op fits).

examples/nvmoe-logits is the correctness gate: it greedy-decodes a
fixed prompt and dumps full logits per step. With CPU weight repacking
disabled (pool tensors are plain buffers, so both runs must use the
plain kernels for an apples-to-apples comparison), stock GGUF vs pack
is BIT-IDENTICAL on OLMoE-1B-7B (32 and 48 steps, also under heavy
cache eviction at NVMOE_CACHE_MB=512) and on Qwen3-30B-A3B (24 steps,
two pool groups, mixed Q4_K/Q6_K layers).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
